                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d782">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">765.84/1915: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Long</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-10-17T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 17, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 17—2:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>729. Department’s 175, October 16, 6 p.m. The matter of the bombardment of Addis
                    Ababa and Diredawa was discussed at the <pb facs="0997" n="895" xml:id="pg_895"
                    /> Italian Foreign Office by my German and Belgian colleagues, and the British
                    left an <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> in which it was specifically
                    mentioned. It was also referred to in the representations of other of my
                    colleagues as implicit in any consideration of the position of the
                    above-mentioned open cities. My representations accordingly in following those
                    of my colleagues also included the matter of bombardment although the main
                    emphasis was laid on the general question of the open character of those
                    cities.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Long</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
